If I want to start a hackathon project with these ideas, where do I start?

To turn Satoshi’s ParaBox from a handwritten concept into a functioning hackathon project, you need to quickly validate the core technical loops and build a scrappy, working MVP. Because hackathons prioritize working software over flawless architecture, your immediate goal is to prove that these distinct web3 protocols can actually talk to each other.

Here is a step-by-step roadmap to get your project off the ground:

Step 1: Define the "Minimum Viable Epic"
Before touching code, scope down the notes into a single, cohesive user flow you can realistically build in a weekend:

Identity: A user verifies their identity using World ID to log into a frontend dashboard.

Routing: The dashboard resolves or assigns them a unique ENS subdomain (e.g., user.satoshisparabox.eth) that acts as their secure data pointer.

Secure Messaging: The user can send or receive an encrypted, high-security alert or audit log via Hedera (utilizing Hedera Consensus Service for a tamper-proof log without complex smart contracts).

Storage: Any sensitive file uploaded is pushed directly to Walrus decentralized storage, with the storage hash linked to their ENS profile or Hedera message log.

Step 2: Set Up the Development Environment
Don't waste time configuring a complex monorepo. Start with a fast, modern frontend boilerplate:

Frontend Framework: Use Next.js or Vite with React.

Web3 Onboarding: Use RainbowKit or AppKit (Reown/WalletConnect) to easily handle wallet connections and ENS resolution out of the box.

Step 3: Tackle the Integrations (In Order of Priority)
1. Identity & Auth (World ID)
Start here, as it gatekeeps the rest of the application.

Go to the World Developer Portal and set up a new action.

Use the @worldcoin/idkit React package to drop an IDKit widget into your login screen.

Hackathon Shortcut: Use the World ID Simulator to test successful verifications without needing a physical Orb on hand.

2. Storage Layer (Walrus)
Get data handling out of the way early so you have something to reference in your messaging logs.

Look into the Walrus developer documentation for their HTTP API or TS SDK.

Since Walrus specializes in raw blob storage, write a simple upload function on your frontend that takes a text blob or file, sends it to a Walrus aggregator, and returns a blobIndex or storage hash.

3. Secure Event Logging (Hedera)
Your notes specify "No Solidity Allowed!" for this layer, which plays perfectly into Hedera's native services.

Use the Hedera Consensus Service (HCS) via the Hedera JavaScript SDK.

Instead of writing a smart contract, create an HCS Topic. When a user uploads data or a message is "auto-deleted," submit a transaction to that topic containing the encrypted metadata (like the Walrus blob ID). This gives you a high-throughput, immutable, and compliant audit trail using pure JavaScript.

4. Dynamic Routing (ENS Subdomains)
Connecting the user's wallet to a custom workspace.

If registering live subdomains onchain is too slow or costly for a hackathon demo, look into NameStone (a popular tool at hackathons for issuing gasless, offchain ENS subdomains instantly) or use standard viem/ethers.js interactions with the ENS registry on a testnet (like Sepolia).

Step 4: Build the "Auto-Delete / Lockout" Illusion
Implementing a true cryptographic time-lock or automated backend cron-job can be risky under a tight hackathon deadline.

The Frontend Trick: Store a time-to-live (TTL) timestamp inside your Hedera message metadata or local state.

The Action: When the frontend detects the current time has passed the TTL, trigger an immediate UI wipe ("Auto-Lockout") and clear the active session keys, forcing a re-verification via World ID to fetch the decryption keys again.

Step 5: Refine the Pitch
The final piece of your notes discusses the physical service aspect—the "Fixer" representative, paper shredding, and environmental offsets.

Do not spend precious time trying to code a paper-shredding marketplace simulator.

Instead, save this for your slide deck and video demo. Use it to frame the business model and real-world impact of Satoshi’s ParaBox, showing the judges that you have thought beyond the code to how vulnerable or non-technical populations would actually use this privacy stack.

