It says the dev server is up and running to ttp://localhost:3000 but it says Safari cannot connect to server

Don't panic! This is a classic "first-time developer" hurdle, and your server is perfectly fine.

Safari is being overly protective. Sometimes macOS and Safari get confused trying to map the word localhost internally, or it is trying to force an encrypted https:// connection on a local test environment that is only running standard http://.

Here are three quick ways to fix this, ranked from the absolute easiest to the most robust:

Fix 1: Use Chrome or Firefox instead (The Hackathon Favorite)
Most web developers avoid Safari for local testing because of strict network quirks just like this.

Download and open Google Chrome or Brave.

Paste http://localhost:3000 into the address bar.

9 times out of 10, it will open up instantly. Chrome is much more forgiving with local developer ports.

Fix 2: Swap localhost for the Loopback IP
If you want to keep using Safari, you can force it to bypass its name-resolution check by typing the raw computer network numbers instead of the word "localhost".

Delete what's in your Safari address bar and type this exactly:

Plaintext
http://127.0.0.1:3000
Why this works: 127.0.0.1 is the universal IP address that literally means "my own computer" (the loopback address). Safari can't misinterpret it, so it directly targets your Next.js project.

Fix 3: Check for an accidental s
Make sure Safari didn't automatically change your text to https://localhost:3000 (notice the s). Local developer environments do not have SSL security certificates built-in by default, so if Safari forces an https connection, it will completely block the page. Ensure it says strictly http://.

Try Fix 1 or Fix 2 right now, and you should see that default Next.js starter page pop up perfectly!

