I got "zsh: command not found: npm"

Ah, you ran into the classic "chicken-and-egg" issue of web development!

When you generated the template project using npx create-next-app, your computer used a temporary, cloud-cached version of the installer tool (npx). But when we tried to run npm install, your Mac realized it doesn't actually have Node.js and npm permanently installed on its system hard drive.

zsh: command not found: npm just means your computer's terminal doesn't know what npm is yet. Let's fix that right now.

🛠️ The Fix: Install Node.js & npm
Since you are on a Mac, the absolute cleanest, most error-free way for a beginner to get npm is to use the official installer wizard.

Go to the official website: nodejs.org

You will see two big download buttons. Click the one labeled LTS (Long Term Support). (This is the stable version that 99% of developers use).

It will download a file ending in .pkg to your Downloads folder.

Double-click that downloaded file and follow the standard installation prompts (it will ask for your Mac's lock screen password to authorize the installation).  
YouStable

🔄 Refresh Your Terminal
Once the installer says "Installation Successful", close your current terminal window completely.

Terminal windows don't automatically know when new software is installed, so closing it and opening a fresh one forces it to reload.

Open a brand-new Terminal window.

Type these two verification commands to make sure your Mac sees them now:

Bash
node -v
npm -v
If it prints out two version numbers (like v22.x.x and 10.x.x), you are golden!

🏎️ Jump Back In
Now that your machine natively understands npm, run these commands to get right back to where we left off:

Bash
cd satoshis-parabox
npm install @worldcoin/idkit
npm run dev
Your server will spin right back up to http://localhost:3000, and you'll be fully ready to test that "Verify with World ID" button!

